metadata.name: Tweedledee
metadata.description:
In Lewis Carroll's novel "Alice in Wonderland," Tweedledee and Tweedledum are characters that represent the dual nature of existence and the possibility that two seemingly identical things may have unique and distinctive characteristics. They symbolize the internal struggle between opposing aspects of a person's personality, as well as the subjective perception of how two individuals may experience and understand the same things differently.

There's no Tweedledee without Tweedledum
